1
00:00:01,681 --> 00:00:03,681
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:00:40,361 --> 00:00:42,441
GRAHAM: Ah, nice fjord.

3
00:00:43,921 --> 00:00:45,281
That is a fjord, innit?

4
00:00:47,041 --> 00:00:48,361
Got your bearings yet, Doc?

5
00:00:50,321 --> 00:00:52,601
Norway. Definitely Norway.

6
00:00:52,681 --> 00:00:54,361
-One of the frilly bits on the top.
-(SHEEP BLEATS)

7
00:00:54,761 --> 00:00:55,761
Stay back.

8
00:00:57,961 --> 00:00:59,521
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

9
00:01:01,281 --> 00:01:04,281
It's fine. It's only 2018.

10
00:01:04,761 --> 00:01:06,681
I thought we'd leapt
into the Woolly Rebellion.

11
00:01:06,761 --> 00:01:07,761
Sorry, what?

12
00:01:08,041 --> 00:01:09,601
The Woolly Rebellion.

13
00:01:09,681 --> 00:01:11,281
In 193 years,

14
00:01:11,361 --> 00:01:14,561
there's a total renegotiation
of the sheep-human relationship.

15
00:01:14,641 --> 00:01:16,281
Utter bloodbath.

16
00:01:16,361 --> 00:01:18,241
I've always fancied the idea of Norway.

17
00:01:19,241 --> 00:01:20,241
What bit's this?

18
00:01:20,721 --> 00:01:21,721
DOCTOR: Don't know.

19
00:01:23,921 --> 00:01:27,841
But 25 miles away,
there's an alpaca farm and gift shop

20
00:01:27,921 --> 00:01:30,681
with a very low TripAdvisor rating.
Soil?

21
00:01:30,841 --> 00:01:32,081
GRAHAM: I'll give it a miss, ta.

22
00:01:32,761 --> 00:01:35,481
-There's a nice little house down there.
-DOCTOR: Oh, yeah.

23
00:01:38,361 --> 00:01:42,841
A cottage in Norway in winter
with a chimney, but no smoke.

24
00:01:43,241 --> 00:01:44,641
Could be a holiday let.

25
00:01:45,521 --> 00:01:47,121
Maybe. Shall we take a walk?

26
00:01:48,321 --> 00:01:51,361
GRAHAM: Me and your nan used to talk
about coming to Norway.

27
00:01:51,441 --> 00:01:52,521
RYAN: And what stopped you?

28
00:01:52,601 --> 00:01:54,801
GRAHAM: Well, just never
got around to it, you know.

29
00:01:59,841 --> 00:02:03,081
Oh, look at that. Someone got
a bit overexcited with the DIY.

30
00:02:03,641 --> 00:02:06,201
DOCTOR: Those panels look
more like barricades than repairs.

31
00:02:07,761 --> 00:02:09,401
Looks like it's been abandoned.

32
00:02:11,401 --> 00:02:13,761
Hey, did you see that?
Someone's in there.

33
00:02:14,641 --> 00:02:16,041
(BANGING)

34
00:02:24,561 --> 00:02:25,761
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

35
00:02:26,281 --> 00:02:27,321
Anyone in?

36
00:02:31,321 --> 00:02:32,881
Quick look? Set our minds at rest?

37
00:02:34,601 --> 00:02:36,761
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

38
00:02:41,841 --> 00:02:43,561
(DOOR OPENS AND CREAKS)

39
00:02:52,001 --> 00:02:54,761
Three locks on a deserted house
in the middle of nowhere.

40
00:02:56,361 --> 00:02:57,441
(DOOR CREAKS AND CLOSES)

41
00:02:58,001 --> 00:02:59,281
Maybe we shouldn't be in here.

42
00:03:00,281 --> 00:03:01,681
There's a child in this house.

43
00:03:03,361 --> 00:03:05,601
GRAHAM: Or some maniac
that collects kids' shoes.

44
00:03:11,041 --> 00:03:12,521
You two, go check upstairs.

45
00:03:13,321 --> 00:03:14,441
GRAHAM: All right.

46
00:03:16,481 --> 00:03:18,081
(CREAKING)

47
00:03:35,561 --> 00:03:38,241
GRAHAM: Ryan, sweet wrappers.

48
00:03:38,561 --> 00:03:39,841
(THUDDING)

49
00:03:46,681 --> 00:03:47,681
(GASPS)

50
00:03:47,801 --> 00:03:48,961
-(GASPS)
-(RYAN SCREAMS)

51
00:03:50,881 --> 00:03:53,481
It's okay, it's okay. I'm sorry,
we didn't mean to scare you.

52
00:03:53,721 --> 00:03:54,721
(PANTING)

53
00:03:56,721 --> 00:03:59,681
Hi. We want to help. What's your name?

54
00:04:00,361 --> 00:04:01,481
GRAHAM: Not hungry, are you?

55
00:04:01,641 --> 00:04:04,881
'Cause these days, I always carry
a cheese and pickle sarnie, you know.

56
00:04:04,961 --> 00:04:06,081
Just for emergencies.

57
00:04:07,961 --> 00:04:10,401
You carry sandwiches with you
every time we leave the TARDIS?

58
00:04:10,481 --> 00:04:12,241
Yeah, well, I've learned
the hard way, ain't I?

59
00:04:12,321 --> 00:04:14,521
I mean, we can go a long time
without eating,

60
00:04:14,601 --> 00:04:17,041
and I get a bit cranky
with the old low blood sugar level.

61
00:04:17,201 --> 00:04:19,601
Now, I always come prepared.

62
00:04:20,281 --> 00:04:22,841
Who are you people
and how did you get into our house?

63
00:04:25,201 --> 00:04:28,401
I'm the Doctor, this is Yaz,
Ryan and Graham.

64
00:04:28,721 --> 00:04:31,241
We were out walking, but we got
a bit worried something was wrong here.

65
00:04:32,041 --> 00:04:34,241
When you say "our house”,
who lives here with you?

66
00:04:37,361 --> 00:04:40,321
If you don't mind me asking,
what's got you so scared?

67
00:04:43,281 --> 00:04:44,281
The thing.

68
00:04:49,041 --> 00:04:50,481
What thing, sweetheart?

69
00:04:52,041 --> 00:04:54,241
The thing my dad
was defending the house from.

70
00:04:54,761 --> 00:04:56,161
It got in and took him.

71
00:04:56,561 --> 00:04:57,921
What did this thing look like?

72
00:05:13,081 --> 00:05:14,281
What's your name?

73
00:05:15,521 --> 00:05:16,521
Hanne.

74
00:05:17,481 --> 00:05:18,841
Are you blind, Hanne?

75
00:05:26,561 --> 00:05:28,721
Please help me find my dad.

76
00:05:31,441 --> 00:05:33,041
I heard the thing out here
before I went to sleep

77
00:05:33,121 --> 00:05:35,281
and in the morning, my dad was gone.

78
00:05:35,361 --> 00:05:37,201
RYAN: You don't know it actually got in.

79
00:05:38,281 --> 00:05:40,561
How do you know
your dad didn't just pack up and go?

80
00:05:40,641 --> 00:05:42,841
My dad would never just leave me. Okay?

81
00:05:43,001 --> 00:05:44,161
-Ryan.
-What?

82
00:05:45,001 --> 00:05:47,281
-How long's he been gone?
-Four days.

83
00:05:48,281 --> 00:05:49,281
Okay.

84
00:05:51,521 --> 00:05:52,921
-Love your top.
-(CHUCKLES)

85
00:05:53,441 --> 00:05:55,961
I'm from Sheffield.
Same as the Arctic Monkeys.

86
00:05:56,281 --> 00:05:57,921
My cousin saw their first ever gig.

87
00:05:58,761 --> 00:06:00,601
My mum saw their first gig in Norway.

88
00:06:01,321 --> 00:06:02,601
This T-shirt was hers.

89
00:06:03,001 --> 00:06:04,361
Where is your mum, Hanne?

90
00:06:05,721 --> 00:06:06,721
She died.

91
00:06:07,361 --> 00:06:09,161
I'm sorry to hear that.
You must miss her.

92
00:06:09,801 --> 00:06:12,161
All the time. So does my dad.

93
00:06:12,681 --> 00:06:13,681
YASMIN: Of course.

94
00:06:14,401 --> 00:06:16,521
And I think what Ryan meant to say was,

95
00:06:17,121 --> 00:06:19,081
obviously your dad
would never want to leave you.

96
00:06:19,641 --> 00:06:24,401
But what if he went out to work
or something and got lost or hurt?

97
00:06:25,241 --> 00:06:27,041
He quit work when we left Oslo.

98
00:06:27,121 --> 00:06:29,801
And our boat's still here.
I walked down and checked.

99
00:06:29,881 --> 00:06:31,281
(BEEPING)

100
00:06:34,441 --> 00:06:37,361
We need to get inside.
It always comes out around now.

101
00:06:37,721 --> 00:06:39,001
The same time every day?

102
00:06:39,681 --> 00:06:40,841
That's when it hunts.

103
00:06:45,441 --> 00:06:47,001
-Poor kid.
-You're not buying that?

104
00:06:47,401 --> 00:06:49,961
Her dad did a runner and she's
making this monster stuff up.

105
00:06:50,081 --> 00:06:51,761
Let's not make any assumptions.

106
00:06:52,721 --> 00:06:54,241
You two, have a look in the shed.

107
00:06:55,241 --> 00:06:56,681
-Graham, let's check out the house.
-Right.

108
00:06:56,761 --> 00:06:58,081
Don't be out here too long.

109
00:07:04,201 --> 00:07:05,361
GRAHAM: Do you miss the city?

110
00:07:07,041 --> 00:07:08,241
HANNE: Sometimes.

111
00:07:08,641 --> 00:07:11,121
But my dad wanted a change
after my mum died.

112
00:07:12,321 --> 00:07:14,321
So what, he came here
to get away from all the memories?

113
00:07:14,401 --> 00:07:17,441
Yeah. And this had been empty for ages,
so it was cheap.

114
00:07:18,041 --> 00:07:20,201
Was it your dad who put these
bars and locks everywhere?

115
00:07:20,281 --> 00:07:21,761
The day before he disappeared.

116
00:07:21,921 --> 00:07:25,201
I told him he was mad.
There's nobody for miles.

117
00:07:26,361 --> 00:07:27,801
But he just said...

118
00:07:28,321 --> 00:07:30,281
"There are worse things
out there than people.”

119
00:07:43,041 --> 00:07:45,241
YASMIN: Ugh. What's that smell?

120
00:07:45,321 --> 00:07:46,481
RYAN: I don't think I wanna know.

121
00:07:51,841 --> 00:07:52,841
(SCREAMS)

122
00:07:53,801 --> 00:07:55,401
(LAUGHS) Did you just yell?

123
00:07:55,481 --> 00:07:57,161
A row of dead birds ain't normal.

124
00:07:57,561 --> 00:07:59,521
Normal for Norway maybe.

125
00:08:01,641 --> 00:08:03,041
You were great with her back there.

126
00:08:03,441 --> 00:08:04,601
I'm rubbish with kids.

127
00:08:04,681 --> 00:08:06,081
Nah. I've had training.

128
00:08:06,681 --> 00:08:08,041
You have to reinforce

129
00:08:08,121 --> 00:08:09,801
whatever it is
that makes them feel safe.

130
00:08:15,121 --> 00:08:16,161
Ryan.

131
00:08:16,721 --> 00:08:19,001
What are they, animal traps?

132
00:08:19,521 --> 00:08:20,721
(ROARING)

133
00:08:21,241 --> 00:08:22,321
It's coming.

134
00:08:23,761 --> 00:08:26,001
-RYAN: Doctor, Doctor!
-(ROARING)

135
00:08:26,681 --> 00:08:28,321
-Did you see it?
-YASMIN: No!

136
00:08:28,401 --> 00:08:29,481
But Hanne's dad did.

137
00:08:29,961 --> 00:08:32,401
He's got a shed load of them
in a... shed.

138
00:08:32,721 --> 00:08:34,721
And that's not normal, even for Norway.

139
00:08:35,081 --> 00:08:36,321
(ROARING)

140
00:08:36,641 --> 00:08:37,641
DOCTOR: What is that thing?

141
00:08:37,761 --> 00:08:39,961
RYAN: I don't know, but it sounds
like it's coming from the woods.

142
00:08:41,921 --> 00:08:42,921
Inside.

143
00:08:48,561 --> 00:08:49,921
We need to secure the house.

144
00:08:50,001 --> 00:08:51,921
Yaz, Ryan, block the back door.

145
00:08:52,921 --> 00:08:55,001
Graham, take a look out
from the upstairs window.

146
00:08:55,081 --> 00:08:56,081
On it.

147
00:08:59,281 --> 00:09:00,721
(ROARING)

148
00:09:00,801 --> 00:09:03,201
(TREMBLING) It takes you away.
It takes you away.

149
00:09:03,281 --> 00:09:04,721
It takes you away.

150
00:09:04,801 --> 00:09:06,161
Hanne, listen to me.

151
00:09:06,241 --> 00:09:08,481
Whatever is out there,
we will keep you safe.

152
00:09:08,561 --> 00:09:09,961
But it takes you away.

153
00:09:10,721 --> 00:09:12,521
-(ROARING)
-DOCTOR: See anything?

154
00:09:13,481 --> 00:09:14,881
Nothing yet!

155
00:09:15,081 --> 00:09:16,161
(SHRILL NOISE)

156
00:09:48,721 --> 00:09:49,761
-RYAN: Whoa.
-(YELLS)

157
00:09:49,841 --> 00:09:51,041
Don't do that.

158
00:09:51,761 --> 00:09:52,961
Why are we not in the mirror?

159
00:09:53,401 --> 00:09:54,521
I don't know.

160
00:09:58,481 --> 00:10:00,761
We'd know if we were vampires, right?

161
00:10:01,201 --> 00:10:02,201
Yeah.

162
00:10:03,521 --> 00:10:04,921
(SHRILL NOISE)

163
00:10:05,761 --> 00:10:07,881
(GRUNTS) Oh, what's that noise?

164
00:10:07,961 --> 00:10:09,921
DOCTOR: Get away from the mirror.
Both of you.

165
00:10:11,521 --> 00:10:13,641
-Keep back.
-Hey, we're there.

166
00:10:14,041 --> 00:10:15,121
What just happened?

167
00:10:15,641 --> 00:10:18,881
(EXHALES) Not entirely sure,
but I really don't like it.

168
00:10:20,121 --> 00:10:21,641
Did you see it change?
What happened here?

169
00:10:21,841 --> 00:10:24,081
Just heard this noise,
come over to the mirror,

170
00:10:24,161 --> 00:10:25,921
and I wasn't reflected in it.

171
00:10:27,081 --> 00:10:28,081
(SHRILL NOISE)

172
00:10:28,321 --> 00:10:29,401
GRAHAM: There it is again.

173
00:10:29,481 --> 00:10:30,841
And that noise.

174
00:10:31,281 --> 00:10:32,361
Nobody move.

175
00:10:34,481 --> 00:10:36,641
Locked it mid whatever it was doing.

176
00:10:37,361 --> 00:10:39,601
Can I just say, I love my sonic.

177
00:10:40,361 --> 00:10:41,521
Now...

178
00:10:41,681 --> 00:10:44,201
When is a mirror not a mirror?

179
00:10:49,761 --> 00:10:50,841
(GRUNTING)

180
00:10:53,281 --> 00:10:55,161
(GASPS)

181
00:10:56,721 --> 00:10:58,201
(GRUNTING)

182
00:10:59,001 --> 00:11:00,161
(SCREAMS)

183
00:11:00,321 --> 00:11:02,081
(PANTING AND GASPING)

184
00:11:03,241 --> 00:11:04,241
I'm okay.

185
00:11:05,001 --> 00:11:07,081
Mostly. Bit of a head wonk.

186
00:11:07,521 --> 00:11:08,881
Otherwise, I'm totally fine.

187
00:11:09,241 --> 00:11:12,561
(SIGHS) Solid seven out of ten.
Six and a half at a push.

188
00:11:12,641 --> 00:11:14,921
What was the noise?
The whole house started to vibrate.

189
00:11:15,001 --> 00:11:17,241
Hi, Yaz. Hi, Hanne. Lots going on.

190
00:11:17,361 --> 00:11:19,321
-Was it that thing outside?
-No.

191
00:11:19,561 --> 00:11:22,561
This mirror in your dad's bedroom
seems to be a portal.

192
00:11:23,121 --> 00:11:24,521
When you say a portal...

193
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:28,481
A doorway to another world or dimension,
or who knows what.

194
00:11:28,681 --> 00:11:30,481
But let me tell you,
it really messes you up.

195
00:11:30,561 --> 00:11:31,561
What are you talking about?

196
00:11:31,761 --> 00:11:33,001
I know. Big thing to find out.

197
00:11:33,081 --> 00:11:35,001
I should have broken it to you
a bit more gently.

198
00:11:35,161 --> 00:11:36,641
But like I said, "head wonk".

199
00:11:36,721 --> 00:11:38,921
Whatever is in the woods,
could it have come through this portal?

200
00:11:39,001 --> 00:11:41,921
Possibly. Don't know. Didn't see much.
I need to take a proper look.

201
00:11:42,121 --> 00:11:43,801
Hey, Doc. Do you think it's safe?

202
00:11:44,041 --> 00:11:45,041
I doubt it.

203
00:11:45,161 --> 00:11:48,601
It's a juddering dimensional portal
in @ mirror in a Norwegian bedroom.

204
00:11:49,041 --> 00:11:50,041
I'm coming with you.

205
00:11:50,481 --> 00:11:51,721
-Me, 100.
-So am I.

206
00:11:51,921 --> 00:11:55,041
And me. Whatever's happening,
I'm staying with you.

207
00:11:57,561 --> 00:11:59,081
I can't let you do that, Hanne.

208
00:11:59,401 --> 00:12:00,841
I don't know what's through there.

209
00:12:00,921 --> 00:12:02,921
You're safe here.
Your dad made sure of that.

210
00:12:03,041 --> 00:12:06,401
Also, I need you to keep protecting
this house from whatever's outside.

211
00:12:06,681 --> 00:12:08,561
-Ryan will stay here with you.
-I'll what?

212
00:12:08,721 --> 00:12:09,841
-Not him.
-RYAN: Hey!

213
00:12:09,921 --> 00:12:11,001
What's that for?

214
00:12:11,961 --> 00:12:14,001
Both of you, stay clear of the mirror.

215
00:12:14,081 --> 00:12:16,481
-It's already tried to lure in Graham.
-RYAN: Yeah.

216
00:12:16,561 --> 00:12:17,921
Hey, I wasn't lured.

217
00:12:18,001 --> 00:12:20,161
It's not like I gave it
my credit card details.

218
00:12:22,201 --> 00:12:23,281
(CHALK ETCHING)

219
00:12:27,761 --> 00:12:30,281
This is a map of the house
with its most vulnerable points.

220
00:12:31,161 --> 00:12:32,601
Make sure you take care of them.

221
00:12:32,761 --> 00:12:33,761
Yeah.

222
00:12:41,961 --> 00:12:43,401
What's your dad's name, Hanne?

223
00:12:43,721 --> 00:12:44,881
Erik.

224
00:12:44,961 --> 00:12:46,321
You will find him, won't you?

225
00:12:47,321 --> 00:12:48,641
I'll do everything I can.

226
00:12:52,841 --> 00:12:53,881
(SHRILL NOISE)

227
00:12:54,281 --> 00:12:56,321
GRAHAM: I'm not really sure
this is a good idea.

228
00:12:56,401 --> 00:12:58,521
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

229
00:12:58,801 --> 00:13:00,241
GRAHAM: (DISTORTED)
Oh! Here we go!

230
00:13:04,961 --> 00:13:06,281
GRAHAM: I can barely see a thing.

231
00:13:06,641 --> 00:13:08,281
DOCTOR: Some sort of space-time portal

232
00:13:08,361 --> 00:13:10,841
has latched on to that mirror,
but it shouldn't look like that.

233
00:13:10,921 --> 00:13:12,481
All these weird shards of light.

234
00:13:13,161 --> 00:13:15,601
It's like the portal's
been pulled in half.

235
00:13:15,681 --> 00:13:18,041
By rights we should have
stepped into another world.

236
00:13:18,201 --> 00:13:21,201
-YASMIN: This is another world.
-Not according to my readings.

237
00:13:21,281 --> 00:13:23,001
GRAHAM: Are we still in Norway or not?

238
00:13:23,321 --> 00:13:24,961
YASMIN: How Nordic
does this look to you?

239
00:13:25,161 --> 00:13:26,161
Not very.

240
00:13:26,241 --> 00:13:28,281
Let's look around carefully.

241
00:13:28,561 --> 00:13:30,881
Hey, Doc, there's some lights
around that rock.

242
00:13:32,041 --> 00:13:33,161
Nice spot, Graham.

243
00:13:33,681 --> 00:13:35,161
Both of you, stay close.

244
00:13:36,441 --> 00:13:38,201
Let's make sure
we can find our ways back.

245
00:13:40,921 --> 00:13:42,041
GRAHAM: Is that string?

246
00:13:42,321 --> 00:13:43,321
Very high-tech.

247
00:13:48,721 --> 00:13:50,241
(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

248
00:14:03,121 --> 00:14:04,801
Hi. Sorry to bother you.

249
00:14:05,441 --> 00:14:06,841
(GROWLS)

250
00:14:07,521 --> 00:14:10,041
Have you seen either a very loud
creature heading that way

251
00:14:10,121 --> 00:14:13,481
or a Norwegian human
possibly heading the other way?

252
00:14:14,001 --> 00:14:15,081
Name of Erik.

253
00:14:15,481 --> 00:14:16,521
The human.

254
00:14:16,841 --> 00:14:18,321
His daughter's missing him.

255
00:14:19,081 --> 00:14:20,481
Such tragedy.

256
00:14:21,281 --> 00:14:23,281
Makes me hungry.

257
00:14:25,721 --> 00:14:26,801
No.

258
00:14:27,481 --> 00:14:29,361
Fine. If you can't help us,
can we have your lantern

259
00:14:29,441 --> 00:14:31,281
"cause you seem to have
a monopoly on light here.

260
00:14:31,641 --> 00:14:34,801
Hmm, no charity. Only trade.

261
00:14:34,881 --> 00:14:35,961
Away.

262
00:14:36,921 --> 00:14:38,801
Lantern not yours.

263
00:14:38,881 --> 00:14:40,401
All right. I was only looking.

264
00:14:40,481 --> 00:14:41,481
Take it easy.

265
00:14:42,161 --> 00:14:43,481
Bird is lunch.

266
00:14:44,121 --> 00:14:46,161
Maybe codger is tea.

267
00:14:46,721 --> 00:14:47,961
Who you calling a codger?

268
00:14:48,041 --> 00:14:49,601
It's you who stinks of your own wee.

269
00:14:49,841 --> 00:14:51,961
That's not my wee.

270
00:14:52,201 --> 00:14:55,681
DOCTOR: Let him go, 'cause you do not
want those words to be your last ones.

271
00:14:56,041 --> 00:14:59,401
(GROWLS) Madam,

272
00:15:00,121 --> 00:15:03,401
my name is Ribbons
of the Seven Stomachs.

273
00:15:04,441 --> 00:15:07,041
I so want your tubular.

274
00:15:08,001 --> 00:15:10,201
Such a shiny tubular.

275
00:15:10,801 --> 00:15:14,121
Because Ribbons did see
the man you seek,

276
00:15:14,561 --> 00:15:16,881
er, trade is now possible.

277
00:15:17,401 --> 00:15:22,201
With this tubular,
you can buy this tasty information,

278
00:15:22,281 --> 00:15:24,201
plus one lantern.

279
00:15:25,801 --> 00:15:27,881
What did he look like, this man?

280
00:15:28,561 --> 00:15:31,201
Oh, no horns, one mouth.

281
00:15:31,761 --> 00:15:32,961
So ugly.

282
00:15:33,561 --> 00:15:38,081
Like you, but such nice big boots.

283
00:15:38,721 --> 00:15:39,721
So, he's alive.

284
00:15:41,281 --> 00:15:43,601
Was anyone with him, or any thing?

285
00:15:44,281 --> 00:15:46,241
You'll find when I take you.

286
00:15:46,801 --> 00:15:48,441
But only with payment.

287
00:15:50,161 --> 00:15:52,881
Tubular, please. Now.

288
00:15:54,241 --> 00:15:57,081
Payment on delivery.
And leave the knife here.

289
00:16:10,121 --> 00:16:13,321
Hey, Doc. You're not gonna
give him the sonic, are you? Look.

290
00:16:14,441 --> 00:16:17,001
He's got a belt full of
massive dead rats with six legs.

291
00:16:17,401 --> 00:16:18,761
Graham's right.

292
00:16:18,841 --> 00:16:20,441
For all we know, he took Erik.

293
00:16:20,721 --> 00:16:23,241
And now, you want us to follow
that nutter into the dark.

294
00:16:23,321 --> 00:16:25,481
No, I want you to follow
this nutter into the dark.

295
00:16:25,561 --> 00:16:27,361
There's three of us and only one of him.

296
00:16:27,561 --> 00:16:28,601
Not counting the rats.

297
00:16:28,961 --> 00:16:31,721
Important to stay quiet, friends.

298
00:16:32,761 --> 00:16:35,681
Here. Light. In good faith.

299
00:16:35,761 --> 00:16:38,561
Follow Ribbons to missing daddy.

300
00:16:42,561 --> 00:16:43,721
RYAN: Have you always been blind?

301
00:16:43,881 --> 00:16:47,081
Basically. I can see light
if it's super close.

302
00:16:47,681 --> 00:16:49,401
Oh. Must be hard.

303
00:16:49,521 --> 00:16:51,161
I don't need you
to feel sorry for me.

304
00:16:52,481 --> 00:16:53,481
Why don't you like me?

305
00:16:53,841 --> 00:16:56,041
-You thought my dad would leave me.
-Okay.

306
00:16:56,121 --> 00:16:57,721
I'm sorry. I was wrong.

307
00:17:00,001 --> 00:17:01,921
Which part of the house
is weakest on the map?

308
00:17:04,561 --> 00:17:07,721
Er, the conservatory.

309
00:17:11,161 --> 00:17:13,081
I mean... I mean the porch.

310
00:17:13,961 --> 00:17:15,641
That's not a map, is it?

311
00:17:15,721 --> 00:17:17,121
It sounded like
she was writing something.

312
00:17:17,201 --> 00:17:18,401
It's totally a map.

313
00:17:18,481 --> 00:17:19,801
What are you hiding from me?

314
00:17:19,961 --> 00:17:21,161
I want to go with them.

315
00:17:21,241 --> 00:17:22,321
The Doctor told us to stay here.

316
00:17:22,481 --> 00:17:23,481
I want my dad.

317
00:17:24,041 --> 00:17:25,041
Let go of me!

318
00:17:29,161 --> 00:17:30,761
Hey, give me that key.

319
00:17:31,481 --> 00:17:33,241
You can't just grab me
and drag me around.

320
00:17:33,321 --> 00:17:34,601
-I could call the police.
-What?

321
00:17:34,841 --> 00:17:37,361
And tell them about the monster
or the portal in the mirror?

322
00:17:37,441 --> 00:17:38,561
How's that gonna help?

323
00:17:38,641 --> 00:17:41,681
Ah, it's not cool you're lying to me
about what she wrote on the wall.

324
00:17:41,761 --> 00:17:43,761
-(ROARING)
-That was closer.

325
00:17:43,841 --> 00:17:45,841
How about we stop arguing
and recheck our defences?

326
00:17:49,121 --> 00:17:50,841
DOCTOR: Where exactly
are you talking us, Ribbons?

327
00:17:51,121 --> 00:17:53,761
Relax. Enjoy Ribbons.

328
00:17:54,321 --> 00:17:55,361
Oh, we are.

329
00:17:56,201 --> 00:17:58,441
So, tell us about these lanterns
you're so proud of.

330
00:17:59,241 --> 00:18:02,081
My design. The only light here.

331
00:18:02,201 --> 00:18:03,241
Where is "here"?

332
00:18:03,641 --> 00:18:07,121
Information is sadly so expensive.

333
00:18:08,041 --> 00:18:10,001
You don't have such credit.

334
00:18:10,321 --> 00:18:11,921
But you live here presumably.

335
00:18:12,001 --> 00:18:14,281
I mean, given there's a portal
right where we found you,

336
00:18:14,361 --> 00:18:15,521
and you've chosen not to use it.

337
00:18:17,841 --> 00:18:20,961
Oh. You ask the clever questions.

338
00:18:21,161 --> 00:18:24,521
I bet your brain tastes so delicious.

339
00:18:25,401 --> 00:18:26,401
(SHRILL NOISE)

340
00:18:27,801 --> 00:18:29,721
DOCTOR: What's that?
RIBBONS: Flesh moth.

341
00:18:31,321 --> 00:18:32,321
Your fault.

342
00:18:33,121 --> 00:18:34,401
Keep still.

343
00:18:35,001 --> 00:18:36,001
(GRUNTS)

344
00:18:41,201 --> 00:18:42,201
(CRUNCHING)

345
00:18:43,321 --> 00:18:44,961
That is one vicious moth.

346
00:18:45,601 --> 00:18:47,161
Won't hurt clothes,

347
00:18:47,241 --> 00:18:50,721
but they strip the meat off your bones.

348
00:18:51,281 --> 00:18:55,441
Luckily, anything can be distracted
with a little bit of food.

349
00:18:57,641 --> 00:19:00,041
Onwards, friends.

350
00:19:01,521 --> 00:19:03,481
Ribbons will clear and follow.

351
00:19:11,281 --> 00:19:12,561
(ROARING)

352
00:19:14,481 --> 00:19:15,481
(GASPS)

353
00:19:24,121 --> 00:19:25,881
(ROARING OVER SPEAKERS)

354
00:19:26,121 --> 00:19:27,601
RYAN: Oh, you've got to be kidding me.

355
00:19:33,041 --> 00:19:34,561
(ROARING OVER SPEAKERS)

356
00:19:34,641 --> 00:19:35,801
(ROARING STOPS)

357
00:19:39,601 --> 00:19:40,761
Why would you do that?

358
00:19:43,041 --> 00:19:44,121
Hanne!

359
00:19:45,761 --> 00:19:49,161
Hanne, you don't need to be scared.
There's no creature out there.

360
00:19:51,281 --> 00:19:52,281
(THUDS)

361
00:20:00,841 --> 00:20:03,801
YASMIN: I've totally lost my bearings.
It's like some kind of maze, this.

362
00:20:04,001 --> 00:20:05,281
DOCTOR: Is this where you saw Erik?

363
00:20:05,481 --> 00:20:07,241
RIBBONS: Oh, no, no, no, no.

364
00:20:07,521 --> 00:20:10,641
Ribbons presents your weakest
negotiating position.

365
00:20:10,721 --> 00:20:11,881
DOCTOR: What are you talking about?

366
00:20:12,441 --> 00:20:15,201
Ah, sadly, you have no umbilical.

367
00:20:19,201 --> 00:20:20,201
(SIGHS)

368
00:20:21,681 --> 00:20:24,241
No Erik, no sonic.

369
00:20:24,601 --> 00:20:25,641
Oh.

370
00:20:26,361 --> 00:20:27,801
(GRAHAM GASPS AND GRUNTS)

371
00:20:27,881 --> 00:20:30,161
Two knives.
Of course he's got two knives.

372
00:20:30,241 --> 00:20:33,121
All we have here is such renegotiation.

373
00:20:33,761 --> 00:20:35,361
You have no way home.

374
00:20:35,681 --> 00:20:37,081
I can show you,

375
00:20:37,161 --> 00:20:40,881
but such delicious showing costs more.

376
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:42,561
Oh, my God.

377
00:20:42,641 --> 00:20:44,881
How can you smell worse than last time?

378
00:20:44,961 --> 00:20:45,961
(MOTHS SCREECHING)

379
00:20:47,041 --> 00:20:49,041
-RIBBONS: Flesh moth is following.
-(GRUNTS)

380
00:20:50,921 --> 00:20:52,601
We must get rid of it.

381
00:20:53,361 --> 00:20:54,521
Or more will come.

382
00:20:54,841 --> 00:20:56,121
(GASPS)

383
00:20:57,601 --> 00:20:58,641
RIBBONS: Final rat.

384
00:21:02,081 --> 00:21:03,201
Not biting.

385
00:21:03,281 --> 00:21:04,441
Can't we ditch the lantern?

386
00:21:04,521 --> 00:21:06,441
No, dark is worse.

387
00:21:06,721 --> 00:21:08,121
What is this place, Ribbons?

388
00:21:08,281 --> 00:21:09,321
Antizone.

389
00:21:09,521 --> 00:21:10,521
Oh, no.

390
00:21:11,081 --> 00:21:13,281
Is this a good thing or a bad thing?

391
00:21:13,481 --> 00:21:15,801
An anti zone is a thing
the universe makes

392
00:21:15,881 --> 00:21:18,401
wherever the fabric
of space-time is threatened.

393
00:21:18,481 --> 00:21:22,281
Like a protective buffer zone
to keep threats at bay.

394
00:21:22,361 --> 00:21:23,361
And we're in the middle of it.

395
00:21:23,841 --> 00:21:25,721
How did you even get here, Ribbons?

396
00:21:25,921 --> 00:21:26,921
Always been here.

397
00:21:28,281 --> 00:21:29,761
-(SHRILL NOISE)
-(SCREAMS)

398
00:21:30,841 --> 00:21:32,001
What's happening?

399
00:21:34,521 --> 00:21:36,321
RIBBONS: Flesh moth summoning its swarm.

400
00:21:36,401 --> 00:21:39,521
Signal kills my lantern.
Too many will come now.

401
00:21:40,281 --> 00:21:41,401
You should run.

402
00:21:41,841 --> 00:21:42,881
My tubular now!

403
00:21:43,121 --> 00:21:44,401
-No, you don't, sunshine.
-(GRUNTS)

404
00:21:45,481 --> 00:21:46,601
(GRUNTING)

405
00:21:48,481 --> 00:21:50,241
How's that for an old codger,
eh, Two Knives?

406
00:21:50,561 --> 00:21:53,401
RIBBONS: Silence. They are here.

407
00:21:53,601 --> 00:21:59,041
Yes. Graham, do not move a muscle.

408
00:22:00,281 --> 00:22:04,081
He wanted us to run,
so stay completely still.

409
00:22:12,441 --> 00:22:14,161
No, Ribbons. Don't.

410
00:22:15,361 --> 00:22:17,121
RIBBONS: No! Not me!

411
00:22:17,201 --> 00:22:20,001
Attack the anomalies! Not me!
(SCREAMING)

412
00:22:24,961 --> 00:22:26,881
DOCTOR: Nice and quiet. Now run!

413
00:22:31,481 --> 00:22:33,681
Keep going. There's a light ahead.

414
00:22:34,441 --> 00:22:35,601
GRAHAM: There's the portal.

415
00:22:42,881 --> 00:22:44,241
(PANTING)

416
00:22:45,241 --> 00:22:46,241
GRAHAM: What was that?

417
00:22:46,961 --> 00:22:48,561
I don't know,
but I think we're safe for now.

418
00:22:48,641 --> 00:22:51,241
Hey, have they moved things
around in here?

419
00:22:51,721 --> 00:22:53,121
Everything looks different.

420
00:22:55,161 --> 00:22:57,241
I don't think that was the same portal
we came in through.

421
00:22:58,641 --> 00:23:00,361
GRAHAM: But if that
wasn't the same portal,

422
00:23:00,441 --> 00:23:01,721
how are we back in this bedroom?

423
00:23:04,681 --> 00:23:07,201
Looks to me like we've ended up
on the other side of the mirror.

424
00:23:20,681 --> 00:23:22,441
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

425
00:23:27,201 --> 00:23:28,361
(SCREECHING)

426
00:23:29,281 --> 00:23:30,281
RYAN: Hanne!

427
00:23:32,521 --> 00:23:34,281
(SHUDDERING)

428
00:23:54,081 --> 00:23:55,681
-(BIRD CHIRPING)
-(DOOR CREAKS)

429
00:23:58,801 --> 00:23:59,961
(DISHES CLATTERING)

430
00:24:14,361 --> 00:24:15,761
-Not interrupting, are we?
-(SCREAMS)

431
00:24:15,841 --> 00:24:17,881
-(SCREAMS)
-What are you doing in my house?

432
00:24:17,961 --> 00:24:19,281
What are you doing in your house?

433
00:24:19,361 --> 00:24:21,761
And how is this your house, Erik?
It can't be, can it?

434
00:24:22,521 --> 00:24:24,161
Who are you and how do you know my name?

435
00:24:24,281 --> 00:24:25,321
Put that down.

436
00:24:25,681 --> 00:24:27,161
We just came through an anti zone,

437
00:24:27,321 --> 00:24:30,161
sent by your abandoned daughter,
and it wasn't much fun.

438
00:24:30,641 --> 00:24:31,841
Hanne is not abandoned.

439
00:24:31,961 --> 00:24:32,961
GRAHAM: Oh, yes, she is, mate.

440
00:24:33,041 --> 00:24:35,521
She's scared and hungry
and thinks you've been abducted.

441
00:24:35,681 --> 00:24:37,601
She's a teenager.
There's food in the freezer.

442
00:24:37,681 --> 00:24:38,801
She's fine without me.

443
00:24:38,881 --> 00:24:41,001
There's a monster on the loose
in the woods outside your house.

444
00:24:41,481 --> 00:24:42,481
No, there isn't.

445
00:24:42,561 --> 00:24:44,001
You seem very sure about that.

446
00:24:44,321 --> 00:24:46,761
It's just recordings, so she doesn't
go out up into the hills.

447
00:24:47,801 --> 00:24:51,521
You turned your house into a fortress
to keep your daughter scared?

448
00:24:51,921 --> 00:24:53,841
To keep her safe while I'm gone.

449
00:24:54,121 --> 00:24:55,761
That's a shocking bit of parenting.

450
00:24:55,961 --> 00:24:57,401
You knew you were coming here.

451
00:24:57,801 --> 00:24:59,041
So, why did you make the bear traps?

452
00:24:59,321 --> 00:25:00,441
Because there are bears.

453
00:25:01,041 --> 00:25:02,721
No monster, but the occasional bear.

454
00:25:03,801 --> 00:25:05,601
Look, thanks for coming.

455
00:25:05,681 --> 00:25:07,361
I'll go back soon, but you can go now.

456
00:25:07,561 --> 00:25:10,281
-I'm gonna hit him.
-No, you're not. I am.

457
00:25:10,361 --> 00:25:11,521
Nobody's gonna hit anyone.

458
00:25:12,121 --> 00:25:13,881
(SIGHS) Long day.

459
00:25:14,281 --> 00:25:16,441
Flesh moths and anti zones.

460
00:25:16,521 --> 00:25:19,281
Now, who else is here, Erik?
Who don't you want us to see?

461
00:25:20,081 --> 00:25:21,201
I don't know what you mean.

462
00:25:21,601 --> 00:25:24,041
Yes, you do. Two plates.

463
00:25:28,001 --> 00:25:32,441
Hi, I'm Trine. Erik's wife.

464
00:25:33,201 --> 00:25:35,801
Erik, you got mirror-married!

465
00:25:36,241 --> 00:25:38,921
No. Trine is Hanne's mum.

466
00:25:40,881 --> 00:25:42,241
Hanne's mum's dead.

467
00:25:42,321 --> 00:25:45,441
In your world, I am, but not here.
Wha... What are you doing?

468
00:25:46,521 --> 00:25:49,401
Is this some kind of alternate reality
where Trine doesn't die?

469
00:25:49,521 --> 00:25:53,961
-I don't know what this is.
-Neither do I. I mean, I died.

470
00:25:54,361 --> 00:25:55,601
I remember it.

471
00:25:56,241 --> 00:25:57,481
But here I am.

472
00:25:57,561 --> 00:25:58,641
(CHUCKLES)

473
00:25:58,721 --> 00:26:02,001
She can't leave. We try,
but she can't go through the mirror.

474
00:26:02,641 --> 00:26:04,321
I know I stayed away
from Hanne too long,

475
00:26:04,401 --> 00:26:07,041
but I kept thinking,
"What if I go, and I can't come back?"

476
00:26:08,681 --> 00:26:11,201
(SIGHS) I can't lose Trine again.

477
00:26:11,601 --> 00:26:13,681
GRAHAM: You gotta get
your priorities straight, mate.

478
00:26:14,161 --> 00:26:15,801
Your daughter needs you. Come on.

479
00:26:16,321 --> 00:26:17,721
Don't you want to see your friend?

480
00:26:18,641 --> 00:26:19,801
What are you talking about?

481
00:26:21,161 --> 00:26:22,801
She got here when you did.

482
00:26:38,081 --> 00:26:40,201
(WOMAN HUMMING)

483
00:26:40,281 --> 00:26:42,401
-All right?
-Yeah, I, erm...

484
00:26:42,481 --> 00:26:43,761
I know that sound.

485
00:26:55,081 --> 00:26:56,801
Graham O'Brien.

486
00:26:58,481 --> 00:27:00,641
You better tell me right now
what's going on.

487
00:27:03,681 --> 00:27:05,081
Don't do this to me.

488
00:27:14,801 --> 00:27:16,001
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

489
00:27:19,481 --> 00:27:22,201
-RYAN: Don't move. Stand really still.
-(GASPING)

490
00:27:22,801 --> 00:27:24,041
It's me. Ryan.

491
00:27:27,201 --> 00:27:29,641
All right, uh,
I'm just gonna sort something,

492
00:27:30,561 --> 00:27:32,481
then we're gonna move together.

493
00:27:33,881 --> 00:27:35,521
There's a light stashed here.

494
00:27:38,441 --> 00:27:39,801
(GRUNTING)

495
00:27:39,881 --> 00:27:42,161
(GASPS AND BREATHES SHAKILY)

496
00:27:46,481 --> 00:27:48,761
All right. Just hold my sleeve.

497
00:27:48,841 --> 00:27:51,121
-HANNE: Where are we?
-No idea. Stay close.

498
00:27:52,481 --> 00:27:53,681
All right.

499
00:27:57,521 --> 00:27:59,001
HANNE: Tell me what you can see.

500
00:28:00,161 --> 00:28:01,801
Well, there's kind of a cave.

501
00:28:02,521 --> 00:28:03,841
Nice cave, though.

502
00:28:04,601 --> 00:28:06,881
You ever been to the Peak District?
A bit like that.

503
00:28:07,961 --> 00:28:10,081
Ryan, you're lying to me.

504
00:28:11,041 --> 00:28:12,961
I'm sorry for slamming the door on you.

505
00:28:13,561 --> 00:28:15,441
I had to get in here to find my dad.

506
00:28:16,521 --> 00:28:18,201
Fine. You want the truth?

507
00:28:19,241 --> 00:28:21,161
The monsters in the woods
were just recordings.

508
00:28:21,281 --> 00:28:23,401
I reckon your dad did that
to keep you inside.

509
00:28:24,321 --> 00:28:25,801
Should've just got Wi-Fi.

510
00:28:26,921 --> 00:28:28,521
He lied to me.

511
00:28:30,721 --> 00:28:32,801
-Yeah.
-And now you're lying to me

512
00:28:32,881 --> 00:28:34,481
about how bad it is in here.

513
00:28:36,241 --> 00:28:37,601
I'm trying to look after you.

514
00:28:37,681 --> 00:28:41,601
I know this sounds daft, but am I real?

515
00:28:42,321 --> 00:28:45,001
That creature on the crane,
it killed me.

516
00:28:46,081 --> 00:28:48,681
But now I'm here with you.

517
00:28:50,681 --> 00:28:52,401
I... I don't understand.

518
00:28:53,921 --> 00:28:55,481
No, neither do I.

519
00:28:56,281 --> 00:28:58,001
Why are you being so off with me?

520
00:28:58,841 --> 00:29:00,281
Because this isn't possible.

521
00:29:00,921 --> 00:29:01,961
I know.

522
00:29:02,521 --> 00:29:04,921
But I'm here, love. I'm real.

523
00:29:06,761 --> 00:29:10,561
If you're Grace,
tell me everything about this necklace.

524
00:29:12,121 --> 00:29:13,281
GRACE: It's mine.

525
00:29:14,481 --> 00:29:17,041
You gave it to me two Christmases ago.

526
00:29:18,081 --> 00:29:20,561
Same year Ryan got me
a different frog necklace.

527
00:29:21,641 --> 00:29:23,361
'Cause I like frogs.

528
00:29:24,441 --> 00:29:26,961
You two didn't check with each other
before you went shopping.

529
00:29:28,321 --> 00:29:29,681
And you're wearing it

530
00:29:30,841 --> 00:29:32,681
as a way of keeping me close.

531
00:29:33,121 --> 00:29:34,681
This is unfair.

532
00:29:37,961 --> 00:29:42,241
This has to be a trick. You... You...
You can't be her.

533
00:29:43,321 --> 00:29:44,841
I feel like me.

534
00:29:47,561 --> 00:29:49,041
YASMIN: That can't be Grace.

535
00:29:49,121 --> 00:29:50,801
-Can it?
-No.

536
00:29:51,681 --> 00:29:53,561
And you can't be Erik's wife.

537
00:29:53,681 --> 00:29:58,081
I know. But we are, aren't we?

538
00:30:01,441 --> 00:30:02,961
DOCTOR: All right. No need to panic.

539
00:30:03,681 --> 00:30:04,841
I wasn't panicking.

540
00:30:04,921 --> 00:30:06,481
I know. I was talking to myself.

541
00:30:06,561 --> 00:30:09,281
'Cause all this is very wrong.

542
00:30:09,961 --> 00:30:11,321
Right. What do we know?

543
00:30:12,121 --> 00:30:16,281
This mirror is a direct portal
between two worlds.

544
00:30:16,361 --> 00:30:18,801
We went into it in the real world,

545
00:30:18,881 --> 00:30:21,001
we came out of it in this world.

546
00:30:21,081 --> 00:30:23,241
But that anti zone
sprung up in the middle,

547
00:30:23,321 --> 00:30:24,801
splitting the portal in two.

548
00:30:24,881 --> 00:30:27,801
-The buffer zone between the two worlds.
-Exactly.

549
00:30:27,881 --> 00:30:30,961
'Cause anti zones only exist
where the fabric of the universe

550
00:30:31,041 --> 00:30:33,681
is under huge, terrible threat.

551
00:30:34,521 --> 00:30:35,561
Oh.

552
00:30:35,881 --> 00:30:39,801
So that means that one must be to stop

553
00:30:39,881 --> 00:30:43,801
this world and your world
from ever touching.

554
00:30:44,841 --> 00:30:47,321
Wait, but that means that
this world is dangerous.

555
00:30:47,761 --> 00:30:49,281
But how can it be dangerous?

556
00:30:49,361 --> 00:30:52,321
Also, what even has the power
to create a copy world like this?

557
00:30:52,561 --> 00:30:53,601
Unless...

558
00:30:54,481 --> 00:30:57,001
Oh, no actual way.

559
00:30:57,641 --> 00:30:59,201
No actual way what?

560
00:30:59,281 --> 00:31:00,921
I've told you about
the Solitract, right?

561
00:31:01,001 --> 00:31:04,761
-Literally never heard the word before.
-Solitract. Solitract.

562
00:31:04,841 --> 00:31:09,241
It's a theory, a myth,
a bedtime story my gran used to tell me.

563
00:31:09,321 --> 00:31:10,481
You had a grandmother?

564
00:31:10,561 --> 00:31:12,281
I had seven, but Granny Five,
my favourite,

565
00:31:12,361 --> 00:31:14,081
used to tell me about the Solitract.

566
00:31:16,681 --> 00:31:20,401
'Cause in the beginning,
pre-time, pre-everything,

567
00:31:20,481 --> 00:31:25,041
all the laws and elements and nuts
and bolts of the universe were there.

568
00:31:25,401 --> 00:31:28,801
The light, matter, maths, and so on,

569
00:31:29,001 --> 00:31:33,241
but they couldn't fit together properly,
because the Solitract was there.

570
00:31:33,921 --> 00:31:35,321
So what is the Solitract?

571
00:31:35,401 --> 00:31:37,601
A consciousness. An energy.

572
00:31:37,681 --> 00:31:40,841
Our reality cannot work
with Solitract energy present.

573
00:31:40,921 --> 00:31:44,441
The most basic ideas of the universe
just get ruined.

574
00:31:46,161 --> 00:31:49,841
Think of it like a kid with chicken pox,
nuclear chicken pox,

575
00:31:49,921 --> 00:31:53,121
who wants to join in, but always ends up
infecting everyone else.

576
00:31:53,521 --> 00:31:57,521
Our universe cannot work
with the Solitract in it.

577
00:31:57,721 --> 00:32:00,001
Your gran told you
this as a bedtime story?

578
00:32:00,121 --> 00:32:02,241
Only when I had trouble sleeping. So...

579
00:32:02,321 --> 00:32:03,801
-What did our universe do?
-(SIGHS)

580
00:32:04,841 --> 00:32:11,401
It managed to exile the Solitract
to a separate, unreachable existence.

581
00:32:12,441 --> 00:32:14,001
The Solitract plane.

582
00:32:14,281 --> 00:32:17,521
And suddenly, everything makes sense.

583
00:32:17,841 --> 00:32:22,561
The universe could finally work,
because the Solitract had been removed.

584
00:32:22,681 --> 00:32:26,281
Hang on. Are you saying
we are now on the Solitract plane?

585
00:32:26,361 --> 00:32:29,441
I wish I wasn't, but I think I am.
I'm scared. Are you scared?

586
00:32:30,401 --> 00:32:32,041
I'm genuinely terrified.

587
00:32:32,201 --> 00:32:35,721
This is a separate exiled universe
that is also a consciousness?

588
00:32:35,801 --> 00:32:39,201
That's what Granny Five said.
A conscious universe.

589
00:32:39,521 --> 00:32:42,121
She also said that Granny Two
was a secret agent for the Zygons,

590
00:32:42,201 --> 00:32:44,041
but she seems bang-on with this one.

591
00:32:44,481 --> 00:32:45,641
But why?

592
00:32:46,161 --> 00:32:48,561
Why has the Solitract copied your world,

593
00:32:48,681 --> 00:32:50,681
including Grace and Trine,

594
00:32:51,081 --> 00:32:53,201
and built a doorway

595
00:32:54,161 --> 00:32:55,761
to our universe?

596
00:32:56,721 --> 00:32:59,841
When you put it like that,
it sounds like a trap.

597
00:33:04,041 --> 00:33:05,681
What are you doing in Norway?

598
00:33:05,761 --> 00:33:08,161
It's the docked ship.
Oh, you'd love it, Grace.

599
00:33:08,241 --> 00:33:10,281
It... It's this whole police box.

600
00:33:10,361 --> 00:33:12,841
And inside,
it's like a massive spaceship.

601
00:33:12,961 --> 00:33:14,601
It goes everywhere and anywhere.

602
00:33:14,681 --> 00:33:16,321
She were telling
the truth that night.

603
00:33:16,401 --> 00:33:17,681
You remember everything, right?

604
00:33:17,761 --> 00:33:19,761
-'Course I remember everything.
-Yeah.

605
00:33:20,721 --> 00:33:23,001
I've been to an alien planet, Grace.

606
00:33:23,281 --> 00:33:24,321
Me.

607
00:33:25,161 --> 00:33:27,121
And... And I've met Rosa Parks.

608
00:33:27,201 --> 00:33:29,121
-Rosa Parks?
-I know.

609
00:33:29,681 --> 00:33:31,001
(CHUCKLES)

610
00:33:31,401 --> 00:33:33,321
Sounds like you're doing fine
without me.

611
00:33:34,921 --> 00:33:36,121
I'm lost, Grace.

612
00:33:36,681 --> 00:33:37,801
I miss you.

613
00:33:38,681 --> 00:33:41,121
All my life, I was looking for you.
Then I found you.

614
00:33:41,481 --> 00:33:43,961
And I was so happy.

615
00:33:44,681 --> 00:33:46,201
That makes two of us.

616
00:33:48,961 --> 00:33:50,361
Then I lost you.

617
00:33:50,961 --> 00:33:52,121
I'm here.

618
00:33:52,201 --> 00:33:53,841
Yeah, I... I miss you so much.

619
00:33:55,401 --> 00:33:56,721
I miss you so much, Grace.

620
00:33:57,121 --> 00:33:59,481
Graham, we're off. Now.

621
00:33:59,601 --> 00:34:01,761
Uh... Uh, fine. Yeah. Come on, Grace.

622
00:34:01,881 --> 00:34:05,721
Yeah. Sorry to be blunt. Hi, Grace.
That's not Grace. No offence, Grace.

623
00:34:05,801 --> 00:34:08,961
-None taken, love.
-She can't come, Graham. She's not real.

624
00:34:09,041 --> 00:34:10,961
-I think you're wrong.
-I'm not wrong.

625
00:34:11,041 --> 00:34:13,321
-She remembers everything.
-I know this is difficult.

626
00:34:13,401 --> 00:34:15,241
I mean, all the crazy things
you've seen, Doc,

627
00:34:15,321 --> 00:34:17,641
I mean, you can't tell me
that you know it's not her.

628
00:34:17,721 --> 00:34:20,721
This whole thing is a con.
I don't think even Grace knows it.

629
00:34:20,801 --> 00:34:23,721
I think this whole world is a trap,
and she's part of it.

630
00:34:24,361 --> 00:34:27,321
Listen to me.
It's her or the real world.

631
00:34:27,441 --> 00:34:28,921
You can't have both.

632
00:34:29,001 --> 00:34:31,241
Please, get inside. We're going.

633
00:34:35,441 --> 00:34:38,321
I need to get this open,
and get Graham and Erik out of here.

634
00:34:39,441 --> 00:34:40,961
Oh, it won't budge.

635
00:34:41,161 --> 00:34:43,121
It must be controlled by the Solitract.

636
00:34:44,201 --> 00:34:46,281
Oh, and I can't force it
with the sonic like before,

637
00:34:46,361 --> 00:34:48,281
because it's clever and it's adapting.

638
00:34:48,521 --> 00:34:51,161
What if you do something
it hasn't dealt with before,

639
00:34:51,241 --> 00:34:53,401
like reverse the polarity or something?

640
00:34:54,801 --> 00:34:57,401
Yes, we can. You speak my language.

641
00:34:57,881 --> 00:34:59,201
RYAN: Keep running, Hanne!

642
00:35:00,001 --> 00:35:02,041
In here. In here. Get down. Get down.

643
00:35:02,201 --> 00:35:04,161
(SCREECHING)

644
00:35:07,561 --> 00:35:09,201
(GROANING)

645
00:35:09,321 --> 00:35:11,401
-I think we're good to go.
-Nice work, Doctor.

646
00:35:11,481 --> 00:35:13,001
Thank you. I do my best.

647
00:35:13,321 --> 00:35:15,481
Graham, Erik, time to go.

648
00:35:15,561 --> 00:35:18,961
-Come on.
-Graham, you heard what the Doctor said.

649
00:35:19,481 --> 00:35:21,281
-Grace, come on.
-I'm not sure.

650
00:35:21,361 --> 00:35:23,321
I can't hold it open much longer.

651
00:35:23,441 --> 00:35:26,321
Graham, Yaz, Erik, now, please!

652
00:35:26,401 --> 00:35:28,281
(SCREECHING)

653
00:35:29,041 --> 00:35:30,081
Run!

654
00:35:35,041 --> 00:35:37,281
There's a portal straight ahead.
I'll distract them.

655
00:35:37,921 --> 00:35:40,801
-(GASPING) What are you doing here?
-ERIK: Hanne, it's me.

656
00:35:40,881 --> 00:35:42,161
(GASPING)

657
00:35:42,241 --> 00:35:45,721
-(SCREECHING)
-(GASPING)

658
00:35:45,801 --> 00:35:49,041
-I heard my dad!
-It's okay. It's okay. I'm here.

659
00:35:49,641 --> 00:35:51,881
HANNE: Where are we? What's happening?

660
00:35:51,961 --> 00:35:54,601
DOCTOR: The portal's adapted again.
I can't open it.

661
00:35:55,321 --> 00:35:56,801
I've got a surprise for you.

662
00:35:57,121 --> 00:35:58,481
It's your mum, Hanne.

663
00:35:59,241 --> 00:36:00,441
She's alive.

664
00:36:00,601 --> 00:36:02,641
-What?
-TRINE: Hanne...

665
00:36:04,521 --> 00:36:06,881
(GASPS) My gorgeous girl.

666
00:36:07,881 --> 00:36:09,001
(GASPS)

667
00:36:09,241 --> 00:36:12,601
I don't know who you are,
but you are not my mum.

668
00:36:12,681 --> 00:36:13,721
-(GASPS)
-(RUMBLING)

669
00:36:13,801 --> 00:36:15,561
Ryan. Ryan?

670
00:36:15,641 --> 00:36:17,241
Ryan's not here.

671
00:36:17,561 --> 00:36:20,161
Wait, was he in the anti zone with you?

672
00:36:20,721 --> 00:36:22,641
He's still in there with those things.

673
00:36:22,721 --> 00:36:24,601
The portal's shut,
and Ryan's still in there.

674
00:36:25,001 --> 00:36:27,241
Well, get it open.
We've got to help him.

675
00:36:27,321 --> 00:36:29,081
-No!
-What do you mean "no"?

676
00:36:29,161 --> 00:36:30,921
(CRASHING)

677
00:36:31,001 --> 00:36:33,881
This world is falling apart
because of us still being here.

678
00:36:33,961 --> 00:36:36,921
You and us are still
totally incompatible.

679
00:36:37,001 --> 00:36:39,161
Erik being here
may have been manageable.

680
00:36:39,241 --> 00:36:42,521
But five of us?
That's a lot more incompatible stuff.

681
00:36:42,601 --> 00:36:46,401
You've gone over capacity.
You need to let us go now.

682
00:36:46,481 --> 00:36:49,401
Is it me, or is this woman
completely mad?

683
00:36:49,481 --> 00:36:51,561
Grace and Trine aren't doing this.

684
00:36:51,641 --> 00:36:55,681
Of course they are.
They're made of Solitract energy.

685
00:36:55,921 --> 00:36:58,161
Hanne can sense it, why can't you?

686
00:36:58,641 --> 00:36:59,801
Why?

687
00:37:00,121 --> 00:37:02,201
What did you build this all for?

688
00:37:08,161 --> 00:37:10,961
Oh! I'm dumb. Of course.

689
00:37:12,081 --> 00:37:15,041
You want the same thing
you've always wanted.

690
00:37:15,681 --> 00:37:16,961
To be with us.

691
00:37:18,201 --> 00:37:20,281
So you've built a world
you thought we'd like,

692
00:37:20,601 --> 00:37:23,481
and taken forms we won't reject.

693
00:37:24,081 --> 00:37:25,641
Don't listen to her, love.

694
00:37:25,961 --> 00:37:28,521
Don't take advantage of him.
You're not Grace.

695
00:37:28,801 --> 00:37:31,841
The real Grace was
a beautiful, smiling superstar.

696
00:37:32,321 --> 00:37:34,161
And you know what she was,
above all else?

697
00:37:34,361 --> 00:37:37,361
She was brave, and she'd be leading
the charge through that mirror.

698
00:37:38,881 --> 00:37:39,921
DOCTOR: Yaz!

699
00:37:40,001 --> 00:37:41,201
(GROANS)

700
00:37:41,281 --> 00:37:42,961
(PANTING)

701
00:37:43,761 --> 00:37:45,721
Ryan? Ryan!

702
00:37:49,321 --> 00:37:50,721
Did I do that?

703
00:37:51,281 --> 00:37:52,761
Oh, I think you know.

704
00:37:53,961 --> 00:37:55,681
I want to go home.

705
00:37:56,201 --> 00:37:59,801
Hanne, don't be scared.
Erik, tell her it's okay.

706
00:38:00,401 --> 00:38:04,161
Hanne, we're in a place,
and it's close enough to home.

707
00:38:04,801 --> 00:38:08,001
We can stay. I wouldn't ask you
to stay if it wasn't safe.

708
00:38:08,961 --> 00:38:10,601
You would, Dad.

709
00:38:11,201 --> 00:38:12,441
You're not well.

710
00:38:12,961 --> 00:38:15,161
You haven't been since Mum died.

711
00:38:16,521 --> 00:38:17,881
You're not my mum.

712
00:38:18,401 --> 00:38:21,641
Whatever you are, I hate you.
Now let me out!

713
00:38:22,121 --> 00:38:24,641
(GROANS AND PANTS)

714
00:38:25,641 --> 00:38:27,601
-(RUMBLING)
-Graham,

715
00:38:27,881 --> 00:38:30,161
Yaz and Hanne
have shown us how to do this.

716
00:38:30,241 --> 00:38:34,281
Ryan is out there in danger,
and this place is collapsing in.

717
00:38:34,961 --> 00:38:38,601
Doc, I know what you're asking me to do,
I just... I just can't do it.

718
00:38:38,681 --> 00:38:40,601
(CRASHING)

719
00:38:41,041 --> 00:38:44,441
She's not your wife.
She's furniture with a pulse.

720
00:38:44,521 --> 00:38:47,241
GRACE: She doesn't know.
She can't know.

721
00:38:47,441 --> 00:38:49,161
Graham, please.

722
00:38:49,321 --> 00:38:52,121
I know how hard this is for you,
but let her go,

723
00:38:52,201 --> 00:38:54,201
or we're all going to die.

724
00:38:54,321 --> 00:38:55,801
(CRASHING)

725
00:38:55,881 --> 00:38:58,961
I know deep down you still blame
yourself for what happened to Grace.

726
00:38:59,441 --> 00:39:01,241
It was not your fault.

727
00:39:01,361 --> 00:39:04,321
Please reject her, because you know
that is not Grace.

728
00:39:05,681 --> 00:39:08,041
Don't leave me, love. Not again.

729
00:39:08,841 --> 00:39:12,161
What about Ryan?
He's in trouble out there, love.

730
00:39:12,241 --> 00:39:15,561
He... He'll be fine. He's a smart lad.

731
00:39:16,801 --> 00:39:18,001
-(CRASHING)
-(GASPS)

732
00:39:18,081 --> 00:39:20,041
DOCTOR: This reality is collapsing,
Graham.

733
00:39:20,681 --> 00:39:21,921
So close.

734
00:39:23,121 --> 00:39:24,481
You were so close.

735
00:39:26,801 --> 00:39:30,161
See, Grace would never let me
leave Ryan in danger.

736
00:39:30,241 --> 00:39:31,841
(RUMBLING)

737
00:39:34,601 --> 00:39:35,801
You're a fake.

738
00:39:37,921 --> 00:39:39,401
I wish you weren't, but you are.

739
00:39:44,401 --> 00:39:45,521
(GROANS)

740
00:39:46,361 --> 00:39:47,601
DOCTOR: Oh, Grace.

741
00:39:48,321 --> 00:39:51,081
-What happened to her?
-Surplus to requirements.

742
00:39:51,161 --> 00:39:52,201
Now do you believe me?

743
00:39:53,081 --> 00:39:54,401
-Erik!
-(ERIK GASPS)

744
00:39:54,481 --> 00:39:56,601
This woman is clearly an alien force

745
00:39:56,681 --> 00:39:59,961
collapsing two realities
and impersonating your dead wife.

746
00:40:00,041 --> 00:40:02,241
-Time to move on, mate.
-But I can't.

747
00:40:02,321 --> 00:40:03,481
-(CRASHING)
-(GASPS)

748
00:40:03,601 --> 00:40:06,121
No, of course you can't.

749
00:40:06,961 --> 00:40:08,001
Fine.

750
00:40:09,041 --> 00:40:10,921
(SIGHS) Congratulations.

751
00:40:11,521 --> 00:40:12,721
Erik wants you.

752
00:40:14,481 --> 00:40:17,161
Just one thing.
This world is falling apart.

753
00:40:17,681 --> 00:40:20,841
I reckon you can only keep one of us.
You sure he's your best option?

754
00:40:24,321 --> 00:40:26,321
'Cause the Solitract
doesn't want a husband.

755
00:40:26,401 --> 00:40:28,241
You want the whole universe.

756
00:40:29,681 --> 00:40:32,401
Someone who has seen it all,
and that's me.

757
00:40:32,721 --> 00:40:36,921
I've lived longer, seen more,
loved more, and lost more.

758
00:40:37,201 --> 00:40:39,401
I can share it all with you,

759
00:40:39,481 --> 00:40:41,881
anything you want to know
about what you never had.

760
00:40:42,921 --> 00:40:45,321
'Cause he's an idiot
with a daughter who needs him.

761
00:40:45,401 --> 00:40:48,321
So let him go,
and I will give you everything.

762
00:40:52,921 --> 00:40:54,281
You're not Trine.

763
00:40:54,361 --> 00:40:55,561
DOCTOR: Finally, Erik.

764
00:40:56,521 --> 00:40:59,161
(GROANS AND PANTS)

765
00:40:59,961 --> 00:41:03,561
You can stop being Trine now,
'cause this universe is going critical.

766
00:41:03,721 --> 00:41:07,281
If it blows, it will take out
the anti zone and my universe, too.

767
00:41:08,121 --> 00:41:09,641
(RUMBLING STOPS)

768
00:41:14,081 --> 00:41:15,761
(GASPING)

769
00:41:36,841 --> 00:41:39,361
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

770
00:41:41,681 --> 00:41:44,361
Uh, why is there a frog in here?

771
00:41:46,921 --> 00:41:49,081
VOICE OF GRACE:
You said I could stop being Trine.

772
00:41:50,441 --> 00:41:52,201
The Solitract is a frog...

773
00:41:53,321 --> 00:41:55,161
who talks like Grace?

774
00:41:55,321 --> 00:42:00,281
My own form is endless, but this frog
is a form that delights me,

775
00:42:00,441 --> 00:42:02,601
as it once delighted Grace.

776
00:42:03,041 --> 00:42:06,561
(SIGHS) There's me thinking the day
had no more surprises left.

777
00:42:06,681 --> 00:42:09,921
Now, please, tell me of your universe.

778
00:42:10,041 --> 00:42:12,161
DOCTOR:
You think words can do it justice?

779
00:42:12,241 --> 00:42:13,761
It's really big,

780
00:42:15,841 --> 00:42:17,801
and incredibly beautiful.

781
00:42:18,601 --> 00:42:21,281
And, apparently,
I've just said goodbye to it.

782
00:42:22,841 --> 00:42:25,761
But the thing
I'm gonna miss the most is the people.

783
00:42:25,921 --> 00:42:27,001
My friends.

784
00:42:27,081 --> 00:42:30,441
I will be that.
We will be that. Friends.

785
00:42:30,521 --> 00:42:32,361
DOCTOR: Right.
Me and a conscious universe

786
00:42:32,441 --> 00:42:34,641
masquerading as a frog. BFFs.

787
00:42:34,961 --> 00:42:37,601
Whoa! Did you just see that?

788
00:42:38,481 --> 00:42:40,241
'Cause I wouldn't be
much of a friend to you,

789
00:42:40,321 --> 00:42:42,441
if I didn't point out
you're not in control of this.

790
00:42:42,521 --> 00:42:45,721
You're wrong. This is my plane.
I control everything here.

791
00:42:45,801 --> 00:42:48,561
So you can see
that it's still destabilizing?

792
00:42:49,161 --> 00:42:51,441
Me being here is gonna kill us both.

793
00:42:51,841 --> 00:42:55,001
You may want us to be together,
but it's not working.

794
00:42:55,081 --> 00:42:56,481
It can never work.

795
00:42:56,561 --> 00:42:59,201
You're lying to me,
because you want to leave.

796
00:43:00,161 --> 00:43:01,881
No, I'm your friend.

797
00:43:02,561 --> 00:43:05,841
But friends help each other face up
to their problems, not avoid them.

798
00:43:06,761 --> 00:43:07,921
This is...

799
00:43:09,001 --> 00:43:12,081
You are the maddest,

800
00:43:12,561 --> 00:43:17,601
most beautiful thing
I've ever experienced.

801
00:43:17,681 --> 00:43:20,001
And I haven't even
scratched the surface.

802
00:43:21,761 --> 00:43:23,481
I wish I could stay.

803
00:43:25,281 --> 00:43:28,681
But if either of us are gonna survive,
you're gonna have to let me go,

804
00:43:28,761 --> 00:43:32,161
and keep on being brilliant by yourself.

805
00:43:34,961 --> 00:43:36,361
I miss you.

806
00:43:38,521 --> 00:43:41,281
I miss it all so much.

807
00:43:41,361 --> 00:43:42,601
I know.

808
00:43:44,121 --> 00:43:50,841
But if you do this, I promise,
you and I will be friends forever.

809
00:43:52,521 --> 00:43:54,321
You have to let me go.

810
00:43:58,441 --> 00:44:02,441
I will dream of you
out there without me.

811
00:44:08,841 --> 00:44:10,081
DOCTOR: Goodbye.

812
00:44:14,121 --> 00:44:15,281
(DOCTOR GASPS)

813
00:44:25,081 --> 00:44:26,441
(GROANS AND PANTS)

814
00:44:26,521 --> 00:44:28,561
Thrown by a frog. Brilliant.

815
00:44:29,481 --> 00:44:30,681
(GROANING)

816
00:44:36,001 --> 00:44:39,681
Flaming rocks!
I'm never coming here again!

817
00:44:39,761 --> 00:44:41,601
RYAN: Graham!
GRAHAM: Ryan!

818
00:44:41,841 --> 00:44:43,841
GRAHAM: You're safe!
RYAN: I've got ya.

819
00:44:44,521 --> 00:44:45,641
Graham!

820
00:44:46,561 --> 00:44:49,001
(GRUNTING)

821
00:44:49,521 --> 00:44:51,681
GRAHAM;
The whole place is disintegrating.

822
00:44:51,761 --> 00:44:53,521
Keep going. There's the portal.

823
00:44:53,761 --> 00:44:56,521
What about the Doctor?
Where's the Doctor?

824
00:44:58,041 --> 00:44:59,481
DOCTOR: Coming through!

825
00:45:04,401 --> 00:45:06,481
(GRUNTING)

826
00:45:12,081 --> 00:45:13,121
(YELLS)

827
00:45:17,441 --> 00:45:19,881
(PANTING)

828
00:45:20,761 --> 00:45:22,241
Are we safe?

829
00:45:22,801 --> 00:45:25,361
From the Solitract, yes.

830
00:45:26,401 --> 00:45:27,921
Don't know if it survived.

831
00:45:29,041 --> 00:45:30,641
But it won't be coming back here.

832
00:45:31,881 --> 00:45:32,921
Shame.

833
00:45:33,681 --> 00:45:34,881
Made a new friend.

834
00:45:35,801 --> 00:45:37,521
A whole conscious universe.

835
00:45:38,841 --> 00:45:40,641
Then had to say goodbye.

836
00:46:04,001 --> 00:46:05,241
(ERIK SIGHS)

837
00:46:12,001 --> 00:46:13,361
What do you think you'll do?

838
00:46:13,961 --> 00:46:15,241
It's time we went home.

839
00:46:15,321 --> 00:46:17,561
It's not good enough for any one of us
to be here now.

840
00:46:19,681 --> 00:46:22,441
-To Oslo?
-Oslo, yes.

841
00:46:23,161 --> 00:46:25,681
To our flat, and some Wi-Fi, and...

842
00:46:26,281 --> 00:46:28,961
-friends.
-(CHUCKLES) Thank you.

843
00:46:29,681 --> 00:46:30,841
Anytime.

844
00:46:31,361 --> 00:46:32,401
Bye.

845
00:46:32,721 --> 00:46:33,881
Bye, Hanne.

846
00:46:43,041 --> 00:46:44,401
DOCTOR: Come on, Graham.

847
00:46:49,721 --> 00:46:51,401
It is a very nice fjord.

848
00:46:58,641 --> 00:47:00,721
(DOCTOR PANTING)

849
00:47:00,841 --> 00:47:03,241
I see the sheep have moved on.
Probably off plotting.

850
00:47:03,561 --> 00:47:04,881
Come on.

851
00:47:10,081 --> 00:47:11,161
(SIGHS)

852
00:47:18,601 --> 00:47:19,721
(RYAN SIGHS)

853
00:47:20,361 --> 00:47:21,521
All right?

854
00:47:23,161 --> 00:47:24,281
All right.

855
00:47:24,801 --> 00:47:26,521
RYAN: Yaz said you saw Nan in there.

856
00:47:28,401 --> 00:47:31,401
Yeah, I thought... Maybe...

857
00:47:33,361 --> 00:47:35,281
But it wasn't her. Not really.

858
00:47:36,441 --> 00:47:37,601
Must hurt.

859
00:47:39,961 --> 00:47:41,001
Yeah.

860
00:47:43,481 --> 00:47:44,761
I miss her, too.

861
00:47:45,321 --> 00:47:46,441
The whole time.

862
00:47:50,881 --> 00:47:52,521
But at least we got each other, right?

863
00:47:53,201 --> 00:47:55,081
(SIGHS) Granddad.

864
00:47:58,561 --> 00:48:00,161
What did you just call me?

865
00:48:00,241 --> 00:48:02,481
Why? You going deaf in your old age?

866
00:48:02,921 --> 00:48:04,361
Come on. TARDIS.

867
00:48:10,721 --> 00:48:12,841
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

868
00:48:13,681 --> 00:48:14,801
(CHUCKLES)

869
00:48:21,801 --> 00:48:23,881
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

870
00:48:29,681 --> 00:48:31,401
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

871
00:48:59,601 --> 00:49:02,561
DOCTOR: Nine distress signals
all coming from the same planet.

872
00:49:02,641 --> 00:49:04,681
-I should have left.
-Then why haven't you?

873
00:49:04,761 --> 00:49:05,881
The battle.

874
00:49:05,961 --> 00:49:09,161
VOICE: You gave me my destiny.

